Key Concepts You Learned Along the Way
Why CloudFront needs us-east-1: AWS requires all CloudFront-scoped WAFs and viewer certificates to live in us-east-1, regardless of where your app runs. This is a hard AWS requirement.
Why we use a prefix list: CloudFront has hundreds of IP addresses that change constantly. AWS maintains a managed prefix list that updates automatically — far better than hardcoding IPs.
Why the secret header matters: Even if someone routes traffic through a CloudFront IP address, they won't know the secret header value. It's a second layer of defense beyond the network-level IP lock.
Why Terraform state imports matter: When resources already exist in AWS from previous runs, Terraform doesn't know about them. Importing tells Terraform "this thing already exists — manage it, don't recreate it."
Why nameservers matter: Route53 can hold your DNS records all day, but if your domain registrar (Namecheap) is pointing to different nameservers, the world never sees those records. The registrar is the authority that tells the internet where to look.
